    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I think the issue here is handling cases where the Status App thinks a name is correctly registred and associated, but the user from outside Status App changed something, such as released the ENS Name, changed the resolver, changed the chat pub key... \r\n\r\nThis also open two cases, the change is done in other devices and: \r\na. the status is closed\r\nb. the status is open\r\n\r\nFor a. this detection would be done by reading the state after login, and comparing if the pubkey changed. if not, just subscribe the events for b. case.\r\n \r\nHere is an example in a pseudo programming language:\r\n```python\r\ncheckName:\r\n  if user.ensName != null: \r\n    resolver = ensregistry.methods.resolver(namehash(user.ensName)).call()\r\n    pubkey = resolver.methods.pubkey(namehash(user.ensName)).call()\r\n    if pubkey != user.chatKey:\r\n      delete user.ensName\r\n      this.warnUserAboutNameRemoved()\r\n    else:\r\n      ensregistry.events.NewResolver(namehash(user.ensName)).subscribe(this.checkName)\r\n      resolver.events.PubkeyChanged(namehash(user.ensName)).subscribe(this.checkName)\r\n```\r\n\r\nYou dont need to make the function in this format, for example, this could be far improved for using less calls from state (as they cost resources as internet or cpu), in case of new resolver everything needs to be checked, but in case pubkey changed, it just needs to delete. \r\nAlso you should consider that resovler can return address 0, and this means that no pubkey can be resolved.\r\nYou also need to consider that method .pubkey might not be available, as the resolver can be set by user to any address they want. \r\n\r\n@rachelhamlin needs to tell us what should be done in UI side for warning user, if need any warning to start (perhaps can be silent). \r\n\r\nYou can see the ENS contracts here https://github.com/status-im/ens-usernames/tree/master/contracts/ens \r\n\r\n\r\nWhen the release feature becomes implemented in Status, it would also benefit from this already subscribed events. ",
